===Etymology 1===
Old High German ''[[reini]]'', from {{etyl|gem-pro|de}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*hrainiz}}, a suffixed form of {{etyl|ine-pro|de}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*(s)keri-}}. Cognate with Old Saxon ''[[hreni]]'' ({{etyl|nds|-}} {{l|nds|ren}}), Dutch ''[[#Dutch|rein]]'', Old Norse {{term|hreinn|lang=non}} (Swedish {{term|ren|lang=sv}}); and with Ancient Greek {{term|χρίνειν|tr=khrinein|lang=grc}}, Old Irish ''[[criathar]]''. More remotely related to English {{term|riddle||sieve|lang=en}}.

====Adjective====
{{de-adj|reiner|reinsten}}

# [[pure]], [[clear]], [[plain]]
#* '''2010''', ''[[w:Der Spiegel|Der Spiegel]]'', issue [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/index-2010-24.html 24/2010], page 131:
#*: Natürlich ist eine Weltmeisterschaft kein '''reines''' Sportevent mehr, sie ist sicher auch ein bisschen Welt- und Entwicklungspolitik.
#*:: Of course, a world championship is no longer a pure sports event, it surely is also a bit of world and development politics.

=====Declension=====
{{de-decl-adj|rein|reiner|reinst}}

====Adverb====
{{de-adv}}

# [[purely]]
#: ''Unsre Beziehung ist '''rein''' platonisch.''
#: Our relationship is purely platonic.

===Etymology 2===
Contraction of {{term|herein|lang=de}}.

====Adverb====
{{de-adv}}

# {{context|colloquial|lang=de}} [[inside]], in here
#: ''Er kommt jetzt '''rein'''.'' -- He's coming inside now.
# {{context|colloquial|lang=de}} [[inside]], in there
#: ''Er geht '''rein''' zu den andern.'' -- He's going inside to the other people.

=====Usage notes=====
Unlike the standard language, colloquial German does not distinguish the meanings of {{term|hinein|lang=de}} ("in there, away from the speaker") and {{term|herein|lang=de}} ("in here, towards the speaker"). {{term|rein|Rein}} is used for both meanings.

